          "title": "The savage irony of futile preparation (3:14-15)",
          "body": "Verses 14-15 are among the most biting in the prophetic literature. The imperatives pile up with mock-urgency: 'Draw for yourself water for the siege! Strengthen your fortifications! Go into the clay and tread the mortar! Take hold of the brick mold!' (3:14). Every command is rational emergency preparation — what any competent military commander would order when siege was imminent. Nahum commands all of it. And then 3:15 delivers the devastation in a single sentence: 'There fire will consume you, the sword will cut you down.' *There* — in your fortified walls, beside your stored water, in your newly-fired brickwork — judgment meets you. All preparation will be the staging ground of your destruction. This is not merely rhetorical cruelty; it is theology. No human contingency plan overrides a divine verdict. When the LORD of hosts has said 'I am against you,' the engineering skill of the most advanced civilization on earth is ripe figs waiting to fall. The locust simile that immediately follows ('It will consume you as the locust does') connects to the extended locust-metaphor of 3:15-17: multiply all you want — the locust swarm that strips everything is both the image of Nineveh's doom and the image of her own unreliable leadership."
